Here is an example of a CSS code that you can use to make all text boxes (input fields) visible on a web page:
```
input[type="text"],
textarea {
  visibility: visible;
}
```
This code targets all elements with the `type` attribute set to `"text"` (i.e., regular input fields) and all `textarea` elements, and sets their `visibility` property to `visible`. This means that these elements will be displayed on the page, regardless of whether they have any content or not.

If you want to target only specific types of text boxes, such as password fields or email addresses, you can modify the selector accordingly. For example:
```
input[type="password"],
input[type="email"] {
  visibility: visible;
}

textarea {
  visibility: visible;
}
```
This code targets only password fields (`input[type="password"]`) and email address fields (`input[type="email"]`), in addition to `textarea` elements.

Note that this code assumes that the text boxes are initially hidden due to some other CSS rule or JavaScript code. If the text boxes are already visible by default, this code won't have any effect.

